i. Section 6.3 - Reconciliation of inventory count per RPCPPE with property and accounting records;
ii. Section 7.0 - Disposition for non-existing/missing PPEs;
iii. Section 8.0 - Derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without an available record of accountability; and
iv. Section 9.0 - Accounting entries and disclosure in the notes to the FS.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Treasurer and the Officer-In-Charge, City Public Market Administration Office to:

a. Execute formal COLs with all the qualified market stallholders, making sure that they are prepared in accordance with the stipulations of the 2015 Market Code of General Trias; 

b. Update and complete the names reported in the list submitted by the City Treasurer’s Office, and reconcile them with those of the City Public Market Administration Office, as well as with the registered business owners per the Business Permit and Licensing Office (BPLO) reports, to ensure uniformity of reports among the three offices and reliable identification of leaseholders;

c. Require all market stallholders to obtain business or permits from the BPLO, or face penalties and closure of their operations under relevant City Ordinances; 

d. Investigate the practice of selling and sub-leasing of market stalls not in accordance with Section 15 of the Market Code and cause the revocation of the lease, if warranted; 

e. Investigate why numerous market stallholders were permitted to occupy two stalls that were not adjacent to each other, to lease more than two market stalls, and to lease stalls from different sections of the market; 

f. Send demand letters to current market stallholders with unsettled accounts, consisting of market stall rental fees and/or electricity bills, totaling P4,048,554.74, including surcharge, informing them that failure to settle their accounts within 30 days from the due date shall be sufficient grounds for the automatic cancellation of the lease rights and eviction; and 

g. Ensure that the provisions of the 2015 Market Code of General Trias, particularly on the issuance of lease contracts, the disallowance of sub-leasing and sale of privilege to occupy stalls, or operation as the primary reason for non-implementation.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
a. Municipal Assessor to coordinate with the Provincial Assessor for the revised valuation of properties located in Timalan Balsahan and include the same to the assessment roll to be provided to the Municipal Treasurer on or before 31st day of December each year;
b. Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor for a copy of latest and accurate assessment roll needed for the preparation of a certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year which should be forwarded to the Municipal Accountant that will serve as a basis of recording RPT and SET Receivables set-up;
c. Municipal Treasurer to properly prepare the Certified List of Delinquent Taxpayer which should include all taxpayers with unpaid taxes and which should be reconciled with the RPT and SET Receivables recorded by the Municipal Accountant;
d. Municipal Accountant to ensure that the amount of RPT and SET Receivables set-up recorded at the beginning of the year is based on a list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year prepared and certified by the Municipal Treasurer; and
e. Properly review and validate the source documents prior to recording of transactions in the accounting books in order to achieve fair presentation of Financial Statements as prescribed by paragraph 27 of IPSAS No. 1.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require all concerned officials/personnel with issued vehicles from the Municipality of Tanza, in coordination with the GSO, to:
a. Present their vehicles to the COA Audit Team for inspection; otherwise, inspection for unpresented vehicles will be deemed missing or non-existing, which may warrant further investigation from the Office of the Municipal Mayor and the COA Audit Team and the taking of appropriate legal action against the accountable employees;
b. Attach the plate numbers and/or conduction stickers/plate/stickers of all motor vehicles of the Municipality and mark all government vehicles with the name of the Municipality for proper identification;
c. Cause the registration of the 49 motor vehicles and the renewal of registration of the 52 other motor vehicles with the LTO in compliance with Section 5 of Batas PB No. 74; and
d. Ensure that all vehicles of the Municipality are insured with the GSIS in compliance with RA No. 656.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Formulate written policies/guidelines limiting the granting of mobile phones and limitations on the grant of mobile phones and plans to public officials and employees taking into consideration the necessity of its usage and the reasonableness of the amount as approved by the local sanggunian;
b. Limit the grant of either the mobile phones or mobile plan subscriptions to public officials and employees to avoid excessive expenditures and submit written justifications on the availment of mobiles phones in addition to the mobile plan subscription charged to the Municipality;
c. Analyze the need to provide mobile phones to Officials already granted with mobile plan subscriptions and ensure that only qualified personnel holding the position not lower than the Division Chief or Department Heads were provided with mobile phone/plan, unless otherwise justified as necessary in their official duty and/or functions; and
d. Require the Municipal GSO to record as Municipal property, the mobile phones included in the subscriptions of Officials, with gadget cash out charged against the Municipality, through PAR or Inventory Custodian Slips (ICS), whichever is applicable, since these Officials already have issued mobile phones in addition to their mobile plans.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:

a. CAO, in coordination with the City Assessor’s Office and CGSO, to furnish the CPDO with copies of the Deed of Absolute Sale and TCTs to update their records of acquired land properties;

b. CPDO expedites the retrieval and collection of documents related to the identified donated properties, in order to provide the CAO with copies for recording the transactions in the appropriate accounts in the books, and to assist the Appraisal Committee in facilitating the appraisal of properties with no recorded MV;

c. CPDO to coordinate with the City Legal Office to facilitate the registration of all unregistered land properties owned by the City Government;

d. Inventory Committee to ensure reconciliation of land accounts among the records of CAO, CPDO, and City Assessor’s Office so that appropriate adjustments could be made on their respective records; and

e. CPDO to coordinate with the City Assessor’s Office to establish policies and procedures for record management, ensuring that all documents related to the receipt, transfer, and ownership of City properties remain intact, complete, and safeguarded.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:

a. CAO and the CGSO/CEO to update and complete the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELCs) and Property Cards (PCs), respectively, to facilitate the reconciliation of their respective records;

b. CGSO and CAO to reassess and adjust the PIP since the original timeline of activities did not proceed as planned, then proceed with the full enforcement of a one-time cleansing of PPE using the procedural guidelines prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 to address the above issues, specifically with the following activities:

i. Section 6.3 - Reconcilation of inventory count per RPCPPE with property and accounting records;

ii. Section 7.0 - Disposition for non-existing/missing PPEs;

iii. Section 8.0 - Derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability; and

iv. Section 9.0 - Accounting entries and disclosure in the notes to the FS.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

a. Direct the City Engineer and concerned contractors to submit to the COA Audit Team a written explanation why the Accomplishment Reports, Letter Requests for Payment, Certificates of Completion and Inspection Reports for the contract works “Imus Logo and Signage” and “Extension Office” with total contract value of P738,586.25 for the construction of Fire Station Building (Phase 1) and improvement of City Operations Center and City Command Center, respectively, were issued which resulted in the payment of the amount despite non-completion or non-implementation of the said contract works;
b. Require the City Engineering Office and the concerned contractors to make a catch-up plan for the completion of the remaining contract works for the construction of Fire Station Building (Phase 1) and improvement of City Operations Center and City Command Center to avoid further delays in the completion and implementation of the projects;
c. Direct the City Accountant to compute and deduct from any money due or which may become due to the concerned contractors, or from the retention money or other securities posted by the contractors, whichever is convenient to the City, the corresponding liquidated damages for the delays incurred in the completion of the remaining contract works of the construction of Fire Station Building (Phase 1) and improvement of City Operations Center and City Command Center if the delay was due to the contractor’s fault, pursuant with the stipulations of the Contracts of Agreement of the projects and the provisions of RA No. 9184 and its Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) and LGUPM of the GPPB; and henceforth
d. Require the concerned City Officials of the City Engineering Office to validate properly the contractor’s work accomplishments and refrain from issuing Inspection Reports, Certificates of Completion and other similar documents if they do not faithfully represent the actual status of accomplishment of the project since the same may constitute as an act of falsification of public documents which may lead to disbursements for unperformed works and undelivered services, to avoid disallowance of the transaction in audit.

Werecommended thattheMunicipalMayor direct the:

a. Inventory Committee to conduct complete annual physical count of all properties of the Municipality, and to prepare and submit a comprehensive RPCPPE as of year-end;

b. Municipal Accountant to prepare necessary adjusting entries for the reclassification of the Semi-Expendable Properties recorded as PPE to the GovernmentEquityaccount;

c. MGSO to maintain PCs per type/class of PPE, in their prescribed format, as the bases and references in the conduct of physical count and subsequent preparationof theRPCPPE;

d. Municipal Accountant to maintain PPELCs for each class of PPE, including the rate of depreciation, date and reference of the source documents pertaining to the PPE, number of quantities received, unit costs and other necessary information, for the verification of the year-end balances and to facilitate the reconciliation of any discrepancy between the balances per books and theRPCPPE; and

e. MGSO and Municipal Accountant to reconcile their respective PPE records to come up with the reconciled and reliable balances of PPE. Should reconciliation of the RPCPPE and accounting records appeared to be improbable, consider availing the one-time cleansing of PPE in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006datedJanuary31, 2020.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the LDRRMC, through the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office (MDRRMO), to include under separate caption the unexpended balances of LDRRMF in previous years and the programs or activities which will be charged to the funds as determined by the LDRRMC and approved by the Sangguniang Bayan in the Annual LDRRMF Investment Plan to facilitate the monitoring and evaluation of the utilization of the funds;

We also recommended that MDRRMO to submit to the Audit Team the LDRRMC Resolution, or any equivalent document, showing the approval and recommendation of the Council to re-align the unexpended funds in CY 2022 amounting to P1,500,000.00 which were utilized on various expenses for CBMS; and

Municipal Accountant to maintain the subsidiary ledgers of the unexpended balances of LDRRMF by year of transfer to facilitate the monitoring of the five-year period in which the funds shall remain in the Special Trust and the reversion of any remaining balance to the General Fund after said period.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Properly prepare SLC for all inventory items which should indicate the weighted average cost in order to provide the total cost of issued office supplies inventory and the timely recording thereof in the accounting books;
b. In coordination with the GSO, gather records and documents pertaining to purchases recorded under Textbooks and Instructional Materials Inventory, and Military, Police and Traffic Supplies Inventory to identify the current or former custodian and status/condition of each item;
c. Validate the noted discrepancy amounting to P1,528,350.00 between recorded year-end balance of Chemical and Filtering Supplies Inventory and physical count as of December 31, 2024. Once validated, prepare the necessary adjusting entry and submit a copy of duly signed JEV to the Audit Team for review and validation;
d. Fully adopt the Perpetual Inventory Method by recording all the acquisitions of supplies and materials, except those purchased out of the Petty Cash Fund (PCF), to respective Inventory account. Likewise, determine the costs of inventory items stock-piled at MDRRMO and prepare the necessary adjusting entry to recognize the same as Inventory and submit a copy of duly signed JEV to the Audit Team for review and validation;
e. Gather documents pertaining to the transactions recorded under the Other Supplies and Materials Inventory account. If determined that those were already issued, prepare the adjusting journal entry and submit a copy of the duly signed JEV and supporting documents, such as Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) and/or Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI), to the Audit Team for review and validation; and
f. Coordinate with all departments with Inventory items under their custody for reconciliation of balances, preferably on a monthly basis, to immediately detect discrepancies and to make the necessary adjusting entries in their respective records, if warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Municipal Engineer and other concerned officials to:
• Coordinate with the NIA, owner of the Land where a farm to market road in Barangay Molino was constructed, and secure a copy of Deed of Donation or MOA granting the Municipality the ownership or right to use the Land for the said purpose, to protect the rights of the Municipality against potential future disputes;
• Ensure that legal documents granting the ownership or right to use the Land is properly executed before construction of any infrastructure assets thereto;
• Coordinate with the Donor of the installed 57 units of steel posts with solar-powered streetlights and secure copy of a Deed of Donation which should be supported by a document showing the acceptance of donation by the Municipal Mayor or his duly authorized representative, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant for recording of the FMV of the subject properties at the time of donation; and
b. Municipal Accountant, upon receipt of the Deed of Donation/s, to coordinate with the Appraisal Committee for the FMV/s of the abovementioned properties at the time of donation and immediately record the same in the General Ledger. Thereafter, furnish the Audit Team with a copy of the duly signed Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) and copy of the Deed of Donation for review and validation.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, at the earliest and practicable period, initiate the one-time cleansing of PPE balances of the Municipality by following the guidelines and procedures on the six activities prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 enumerated below, to eliminate any discrepancies or deviations between accounting and property records and to establish an accurate and verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability PPE balances:
1. Preliminary activities prior to the conduct of inventory taking;
2. Inventory taking;
3. Reconciliation of inventory count per RPCPPE with property and accounting records;
4. Disposition procedures for non-existing/missing PPEs;
5. Procedures in the derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability; and
6. Accounting entries and disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. In coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), submit a written explanation to this Audit Team, together with supporting documents, regarding the observations noted including especially on the procurement activities undertaken but not included in the APP aggregating procurement activities relative to the said amount of P251,272,722.34, otherwise, payments relative to the said procurement activities shall be disallowed in audit;
b. Ensure that the APP of the Municipality for CY 2024 and succeeding years are in accordance with the requirements on the preparation of the APP under GPPB Circular No. 07-2015 and submit the same to the COA Audit Team as accompanying document to the Annual Budget;
c. Instruct the BAC to report all bid results, regardless of modality, in the Report of Bid Results submitted and uploaded in the FDPP and henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA No. 9184 and related issuances regarding procurement and the preparation of relevant plans and documents.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Reconstitute the Inventory Committee and require them to conduct complete physical count of the Municipality’s PPE according to their prepared PIP and prepare the corresponding RPCPPE following the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2020-006;
b. Direct the Officer-in-Charge (OIC)-General Services Officer (GSO) to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Engineer in securing the necessary documents like land titles, contracts and disbursement payments of land acquisition and construction of infrastructure assets as basis in recording and updating their respective PPE Property Cards (PC);
c. Require the OIC-GSO to update all PCs and the records based on the latest RPCPPE; and
d. Require the OIC-GSO and Municipal Accountant to exert their best efforts to reconcile their respective PPE records to come up with the reconciled balances of the PPE accounts to be presented in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Instruct the Market Administrator to strictly enforce the provisions of the Municipal Market Code and the contract of lease of market stalls and cause the revocation or cancellation of lease agreement/ certificate of award of stallholders in case of failure of the delinquent stallholders to immediately comply with the demand of the Municipal Treasurer to settle their liabilities after observing due process of law; 
b. Require the Market Administrator, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer to submit the List/Schedule of Lessees with delinquent accounts and with current unpaid rental fees as of December 31, 2022 to the Municipal Accountant for recording as Accounts Receivable; 
c. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary JEV based on the Schedule of Lessees with delinquent accounts and with current unpaid rental fees as of December 31, 2022; and
d. Instruct the Market Administrator and Municipal Treasurer to consistently send demand/ collection letters to delinquent Tenants/ Lessees, and to recommend to the Market Board the termination of contracts of those who continuously refuse to comply with their demand for payments, otherwise Notice of Charge will be issued by the Audit Team that will include all Municipal Officials who must but did not exercise due diligence or take necessary action to collect the amount due the Municipal Government.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. Municipal Accountant to refrain from recording the procurement or receipt of supplies and materials to expense account, but instead course them thru the inventory account in consonance with the Perpetual Inventory System of accounting;
b. Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer or the designated Supply/Property Officer, to maintain SLCs and Stock Cards, respectively;
c. Municipal Treasurer or the designated Supply/Property Officer, to sign the acceptance portion of the AIR in the deliveries of procured goods;
d. Municipal Treasurer or the designated Supply/Property Officer, to prepare Requisition Issue Slip (RIS) for issuances of supplies/materials and to consolidate the issuances on a weekly basis using the SSMI and furnish the Municipal Accountant with copies thereof for recording in the books of cost of issued items; and
e. Municipal Treasurer or the designated Supply/Property Officer, to conduct the required semi-annual actual count of inventory items and prepare and submit RPCI to COA every January 31 and July 31.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a) BAC to ensure that the bidding documents contain Instruction to Bidders, Bid Data Sheets, General Conditions of the Contract (GCC) and the Special Conditions of the Contract (SCC) to clearly and adequately define the obligations, duties and/or functions of the winning Bidder, in accordance with the Philippine Bidding Documents issued by the GPPB;
b) BAC to ensure that the submitted Required Forms of the contractor contain the mandatory provisions stated in Item 6.0 of GPPB Circular No. 04-2020 and disqualify non-complying bidders;
c) BAC to evaluate the technical and financial documents of all bids submitted by the bidders using a checklist of the required documents using a non-discretionary “pass/fail” criterion;
d) BAC Secretariat to post the NOA, NTP and the approved contracts of procurement projects in the PhilGEPS website within the prescribed dates, in compliance with Sections 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of the RIRR of RA No. 9184;
e) BAC and the Technical Working Group (TWG) to submit written justification on why the submitted performance securities were accepted despite absence of material dates thereon and/or alteration of the contractor’s name, for evaluation of the Audit Team, and to take appropriate action against the subject contractor and other responsible officials, if warranted; and
f) Municipal Accountant to make sure that all payments to suppliers and contractors are supported with complete and correct documentation before processing them for payment; otherwise, transactions will be suspended in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. BAC to comply with the mode of procurement indicated in the approved APP, otherwise prepare a BAC Resolution justifying or recommending to the HOPE why competitive bidding or the original mode of procurement will not be pursued, for his approval, and thereafter reflect these changes in the APP;
b. BAC Secretariat to post the RFQ, NOA, approved contracts or purchase orders, and the NTP, if necessary, for projects with ABCs of more than P50,000.00, in the PhilGEPS website, website of the Municipality and conspicuous places within the premises of the LGU; and thereafter ensure that such postings are documented and attached to the disbursement vouchers;
c. BAC to prepare the RFQ containing all essential information and instructions for the supplier/contractors such as due dates for submission of quotations and documentary requirements, time or duration of delivery, among others, to avoid confusion and misinterpretations; otherwise conduct a pre-bid conference for suppliers/contractors to discuss said information;
d. BAC to prepare a BAC Resolution recommending award of the contact to the winning bidder, for the approval of the HOPE before entering into a contact or purchase order;
e. BAC to submit to the COA Audit Team, for our validation, the lacking supplier’s requirements such as Mayor’s Permit, PhilGEPS registration number, Omnibus Sworn Statements (OSS) and/or PCAB License, if required, for transactions enumerated in Appendix 1; and thereafter make sure that these requirements are automatically attached to the disbursement vouchers; and
f. Municipal Accountant to ensure that all the above documentary requirements are attached to the disbursement vouchers before processing them for payment, otherwise transactions with incomplete documentations will be suspended and/or disallowed in audit.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. analyze and identify the consultants whose services or functions could be performed by existing plantilla personnel to minimize the cost of Consultancy Fees incurred by the Municipality; and ensure that in the hiring of consultants for the completion of a specific project/program/activity, services to be rendered are highly technical or special in nature that require skilled experts in their respective fields to avoid unnecessary expenditures;
b. direct the Municipal Accountant or any concerned Office to make sure that accomplishments of the consultants match with the services/deliverables required from them based on their contracts, otherwise, payments should not be made if there are unmet or unaccomplished deliverables/services;
c. direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that complete and proper documentations were attached to the disbursement vouchers before processing them for payment; and
d. direct other concerned officials to submit a written justification on payments made to consultants on months where the NOA, NTP, and contracts for their services were not yet executed.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to update and complete the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards (PPELCs) and property cards, respectively, and to compare them with the RPCPPE and submit the same to the Inventory Committee to be used as inventory working papers and on this basis, to revisit and adjust the timeline of inventory-taking and other activities in the Physical Inventory Plan (PIP);
b. direct the Inventory Committee, together with the GSO and Municipal Accounting Office, to revisit the COA Circular No. 2020-006, particularly the guidelines on how to conduct the inventory taking that would likely resolve the issues on the whereabouts and condition of the PPE, and on how to assign or establish cost/value based on the market/fair value of PPE or by appraisal, in instances when the unit values or costs of the PPE, including the subject land properties, were lacking or not available from property records;
c. henceforth, direct the GSO and Municipal Accounting Office to proceed with the following activities of One-Time Cleansing of PPE using the procedural guidelines prescribed in subject circular, especially to address the issue on unaccounted PPE and those which were only presented in lump-sum amounts:
i. Section 6.3 - Reconcilation of inventory count per RPCPPE with property and accounting records;
ii. Section 7.0 - Disposition for non-existing/missing PPEs;
iii. Section 8.0 - Derecognition of non-existing/missing PPEs without available record of accountability; and
iv. Section 9.0 - Accounting entries and disclosure in the notes to the Financial Statements

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Accountant and General Services Office to conduct preliminary activities such as the updating and comparison of their respective records of PPE using the available latest Report of Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) and other property records prior to the preparation of Physical Inventory Plan (PIP). After which, it is recommended that the Inventory Committee and other concerned officials adhere to the guidelines provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006, to wit:

a. prepare and submit the PIP for approval of the City Mayor and submit a copy thereof to the COA at least 10 days before the one-time scheduled start of inventory-taking PPE activities;

b. ensure that property stickers specify vital information on the PPE items;

c. maintain the PCs categorized per class of PPE;

d. prepare the consolidated RPCPPE classified according to type/category for reconciliation with the PPE records provided by the City Accounting Office;

e. conduct disposition and de-recognition procedures for missing or unaccounted PPE, if any; and

f. conduct other procedures as may be necessary to complete and finish the one-time cleansing of PPE availed of by the City.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
a) Municipal Accountant to make sure that all progress and final payments to suppliers and contractors are supported with complete documentation, to avoid suspension in audit; 
b) Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to ensure that the bidding documents contain the General Conditions of the Contract (GCC) and the Special Conditions of the Contract (SCC) to clearly and adequately define the obligations, duties and/or functions of the winning Bidder, in accordance with the Philippine Bidding Documents issued by the GPPB; 
c) BAC to ensure that the submitted Required Forms of the contractor contain the mandatory provisions stated in Item 6.0 of GPPB Circular No. 04-2020 and disqualify non-complying bidders; and 
d) Municipal Engineering Office to require the contractors to prepare and submit the As-Built plans for all infrastructure projects awarded to them upon reaching 95 percent completion for their review, and to not issue a Certificate of Completion unless the As-Built plan has been approved.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
a. City Accountant and General Services Officer (GSO) to exert more efforts to reconcile the discrepancy between the accounting records of PPE and RPCPPE;
b. City Accountant and the GSO to submit to the Audit Team the complete IIRUPs that were used as basis for dropping unserviceable PPEs totaling P27,555,458.18 as provided in the Manual on Disposal of Government Unserviceable Properties, and;
c. City Accountant to exert extra efforts to retrieve the records of the subject PPEs to enable the computation of depreciation expense and to make the necessary adjustments in the books.

a. City Budget Office to allocate no less than five percent of the Annual Budget for the LDRRMF, in compliance with Section 21 of RA No. 10121;
b. City Planning and Development Office and the CDRRMO to provide specific timetables/schedules of the implementation of all PPAs in the City Disaster Risk Reduction Management Annual Investment Plan (AIP) for guidance and monitoring; and
c. HRMO to intensify its efforts to widely inform the public of the need to fill up four regular plantilla positions in the LDRRMO, and ensure that qualified City employees are assigned to the LDRRMO.

We recommended that the City Mayor undertake the following:
• take a lead role in direction-setting, advocacy, planning, monitoring and evaluation, and technical advisory;
• spearhead the preparation of the annual and performance-based LGU GAD Plan and Budget responsive to the gender issues and concerns identified in the locality making sure that its total amount corresponds to not less than five percent of the annual budget;
• prepare a comprehensive Annual GAD Accomplishment Report incorporating all the accomplishments of the different departments of the City that are GAD-related; and
• set up appropriate systems and mechanisms to ensure the generation, processing, review and updating of sex-disaggregated data or GAD database to serve as basis in performance-based and gender-responsive planning and budgeting; and ensure that allocations in the GAD Plan and Budget have corresponding gender issues to be addressed.

We recommended for the following corrective measures:
The City Accountant and the General Services Officer should exert more effort to reconcile the difference of P35,921,924.37 existing between the accounting records of PPE and RPCPPE;
The General Services Office should conduct physical inventory of assets taken up in the Special Education Fund books with acquisition cost of P2,397,011.59 to determine its actual existence and condition and prepare the Report of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;
The Accounting Office should provide the data on Accumulated Depreciation of the unserviceable property in the IIRUP; and
The City Mayor should create Appraisal and Disposal Committee to enable the proper disposal of the reported unserviceable property.

We recommended that the City Accountant undertake the following:
Reconcile the Real Property Tax Receivables and Special Education Tax Receivables with the Records of Real Property Tax Delinquencies maintained by the City Treasurer’s Office;
Coordinate with the City Treasurer’s Office to obtain the desired information on the Real Property Tax Receivables and Special Education Tax Receivables such as the name of taxpayers, amount and period of delinquencies, and other related information;
Maintain and update regularly the Subsidiary Ledgers.

We recommended that the City GAD Focal Point System fully implement the provisions of City Ordinance No. 07-3154 and mainstream GAD perspectives in the LGUs policies, plans and programs by undertaking the following:
Take a lead role in direction-setting, advocacy, planning, monitoring and evaluation, and technical advisory;
Spearhead the preparation of the annual and performance-based LGU GAD Plan and Budget responsive to the gender issues and concerns identified in the locality making sure that its total amount corresponds to not less than five percent of the annual budget;
Prepare a comprehensive Annual GAD Accomplishment Report incorporating all the accomplishments of the different departments of the City that are GAD-related;
Set up appropriate systems and mechanisms to ensure the generation, processing, review and updating of sex-disaggregated data or GAD database to serve as basis in performance-based and gender-responsive planning and budgeting; and
Ensure that allocations in the GAD Plan and Budget have corresponding gender issues to be addressed.
